# Live Edge Slabs 101: What to Know Before You Buy

Live edge furniture has become one of the most requested looks in home design — and for good reason. There's nothing quite like a table that still shows the natural silhouette of the tree it came from. But a live edge slab is also a bigger investment than a standard board, and first-time buyers often aren't sure what actually matters when picking one out. Here's what to look for.

## Thickness Matters More Than You'd Think

Slab thickness affects both looks and structural integrity. A thin slab can work for a shelf or wall art, but for a dining table or desk that needs to span a distance without sagging, you'll want a thicker slab — or a base design that adds extra support underneath. Always check the listed thickness before you buy, and think about your base and span together, not the slab alone.

## Moisture Content and Stability

A slab that hasn't fully dried can continue to move, crack, or cup even after it's built into furniture. This is one of the most common mistakes first-time buyers make: falling in love with a slab's figure without asking whether it's actually ready to build with. Every slab we sell has gone through a proper drying process, but if you're ever buying elsewhere, it's worth asking directly.

## Cracks, Checks, and Voids Aren't Always a Flaw

Natural checking (small cracks radiating from the ends of a slab) and voids are common in live edge wood and don't necessarily mean the slab is compromised. Many woodworkers actually fill these with epoxy to create a river-style feature rather than trying to avoid them entirely. The key is knowing what you're looking at before you commit — which is why we photograph every slab individually rather than using a stock image.

## Book-Matching: Two Slabs, One Tree

If you're building a larger table or want a dramatic, symmetrical grain pattern, ask about book-matched pairs — two slabs cut from the same log and opened like a book so their grain mirrors across the seam. It's one of the most striking things you can do with a live edge project, but it only works if the slabs are kept together and cut close to each other in the log.

## Species Changes the Character of the Piece

The species you choose shapes the whole feel of the finished piece. Monkeypod offers wide, dramatic slabs with strong contrast between heartwood and sapwood. Koa brings warmth and shimmer but usually in smaller widths. Chocolate albizia adds bold, marbled spalting for a piece that reads as art as much as furniture. Think about the room the piece is going into and the mood you're after before you fall for the first slab you see.

## Before You Order

- Confirm the finished dimensions (length, width, thickness) fit your space and base plan
- Ask about moisture content if it's not listed
- Look closely at the individual photos for cracks, voids, or bark inclusions near the edge
- Consider whether you want a book-matched pair
- Factor in that a slab this individual can't be reordered — once it's sold, that exact grain pattern is gone

